LAST CHANCE to register for our #GenSea Water Career Panel on January 24th!

It's time to meet the final speaker: Zachary Plopper, Senior Environmental Director at the Surfrider Foundation!

As Environmental Director, Zach leads Surfrider’s national environmental team to protect our oceans, waves and beaches. 

With more than a decade of work in the United States, Latin America, and other regions of the world, Zach is a leading expert in ecosystem-based and advocacy-driven coastal and marine conservation. 

Before joining Surfrider, Zach was the Associate Director of WILDCOAST, where he established the largest private protectorate of coastline in northwest Mexico, helped strengthen California’s network of marine protected areas, and advanced blue carbon ecosystem conservation as a nature-based climate solution in California and Mexico. 

Zach is an avid surfer and currently resides in Ventura County with his wife and two children. He has an MA from the University of California, Los Angeles and a BA from the University of California, San Diego in Urban Planning.

You can hear more from Zach on January 24th! Register at joingensea.org/events

#WeAreGenSea

Most people don't even know what krill are, but these tiny crustaceans are crucial to all life on earth.

On August 11, we celebrate World Krill Day! This special occasion honors our small yet mighty friends who reside in the Southern Oceans near Antarctica. 
Responsible for the largest single carbon sink on earth, critical to oxygen production and biodiversity in the ocean...krill truly are the superheroes of the ocean.

Join me and @ashlancousteau as we discuss the reality of why krill, a little known creature in the Southern Ocean is the superhero of the ocean and why it needs our help. The krill fishery around Antarctica is the biggest climate catastrophe that no one is talking about. Find out what we're doing to solve it and how you can help.

Happy #WorldKrillDay! I am so excited to announce the pre-launch of our new company SeaVoir. This has been a passion for the past several years and now we are pre-launching on a day where we celebrate the superhero of the ocean - krill.
Our entirely algae-based Omega 3s, which are not only better for our health than krill/fish oil, are helping to replace the terribly destructive krill oil fishery thus helping to restore and protect the ocean.

Unlike exploitative krill/fish oil based supplements, SeaVoir's Omega 3s are clinically proven to be absorbed 1.7x better, are toxin-free, and don't leave you with nasty fish burps!

Visit the link in our bio to learn more about how SeaVoir's Omega 3s are the solution to the climate catastrophe no one is talking about.

The truth about fish and krill oil Omega 3s is in a word...gross. @ashlancousteau and I discuss what you should know if you take fish or krill oil Omega and why you deserve better. Make the switch to algae, it's where fish and krill get their Omegas from so why shouldn't you. Better for you, toxin free, more absorbable, and plant based and NO FISH BURPS...oh and it's better for the planet too.

In Barbados for a meeting with Prime Minister @mamottley & @exportbarbadosbidc @pcousteau and I joined by some of our senior team including Andrew Snowhite & @Sarahlucasmemo. The week centered around a discussion of how our company Voyacy Ventures can  collaborate with local stakeholders to expand their coral restoration initiatives exponentially. @visitBarbados has extraordinary leadership and wonderful people. It is so refreshing to see a place that is committed to building a blue economy that can help restore the environment and provide economic growth at the same time. Lot's of work to do but we are looking forward to next steps and collaborating with Barbados on creating a pioneering model that can help set a new standard for restoring coastal marine ecosystems at scale.

Some highlights from our time spent in the beautiful waters of #Barbados! Every time we get a chance to experience the incredible beauty of our oceans, we are reminded how important the protection of their health is.

In case you didn't see, our last WeekDay Roundup was a collaborative post between ourselves and our wonderful friends at the Environmental Media Association! We are so excited to partner with them to share our fledgling news broadcast to a larger audience, increasing awareness about just some of the important stories occurring on our ocean planet.

We can't wait to continue our friendship into the future.

We were honored to write an article for Green Money on our experience visiting Antarctica for the first time, and of the powerful impression that our journey made on us as to the importance of our Southern Oceans.

Even though the Antarctic ecosystem is responsible for sequestering most of the World's yearly carbon dioxide emissions, its importance is often overlooked. But as climate conditions continue to worsen from human-influenced pollution, this essential region of our ocean planet is under great threat from a number of issues, namely, the exploitation and over-fishing of Antarctic Krill.

Read the full article in the link in @seavoir.wellness bio!
